Out of pure habit (dangerous, stupid habit), I reached for my phone.
The light caught my torso the way it always had: a perfect diagonal across my ribs, shadow pooling under the curve of my chest. Reflex took over. I lifted the phone, adjusted the angle, flexed just enough. Click.
It was a beautiful photo. Of course it was.
I posted it before my brain caught up. Caption vague, atmospheric, suggestive (the kind that invited a thousand fantasies without giving away anything real).
Within minutes the notifications exploded. Fire emojis. Thirsty messages. Women I hadn’t spoken to in months sliding back into my DMs like nothing had changed.
It felt good for exactly four seconds.
Then it felt like poison.
