Chapter 9

She told me she’d watched the new video three times.
That my rawness unsettled her (not because it was weak, but because it asked her to be raw too).
That she had pulled away because she was terrified of mattering too much, of losing the protective distance she’d always kept.
Her last line:
“If you want to talk (really talk), I’ll be at our café tomorrow at 10.”
I arrived twenty minutes early, heart in my throat.
She was already there, reading, ashgold eyes calm over the top of her book.
When she looked up there was no mask, no test, no armor.
